[2] Philippines (Zamboanga City)
Date: Tue 13 Feb 2018 15:05 PHT
Source: Zamboanga Today [edited]
http://www.zamboangatoday.ph/index.php/top-stories/23554-measles-outbreak-declared-in-zambo.html


Mayor Beng Climaco has declared a measles outbreak in Zamboanga City in view of the 1343 percent increase in measles cases recorded from [1 Jan-1 Feb this 2018].

This, based on Executive Order [EO] BC 333-2018 issued 9 Feb 2018 per recommendation of the City Health Office [CHO].

The EO directs the CHO through Officer-in-charge Dr Dulce Amor Miravite to "institute, undertake and implement preventive and proactive measures to effectively address" the outbreak.

The CHO has recorded 101 suspected measles cases during the 1st 4 months of the year [2018] representing a 1343 percent increase in the number of cases as compared to the same period last year [2017]. The number of cases is above the outbreak threshold level, thus, the declaration.

Dr Miravite said 49 percent of those with suspected measles were males while 51 percent were females. At least 34 of the 101 cases belong to the 1-5 years age group.

The highest proportion of cases have no history of immunization, it was noted.

Mayor Climaco said the Local Government Code mandates every local government unit to promote the health and safety as well as to preserve the comfort and convenience of their inhabitants, "thus the need to issue an order declaring a Measles Outbreak in the city.

Meanwhile, Dr Miravite said the CHO in partnership with the DOH [Department of Health] would intensify measles immunization activities to children aged 6 months-59 months starting 19 Feb 2018, through the different health centers in the city.

Aside from the catch up immunization, the CHO is also intensifying advocacy to encourage parents to submit their children to immunization amidst the Dengvaxia scare.

The CHO suspects 2 possible reasons for the increase in measles cases in the city, 1) the cases recorded were obtained in other places, and 2) there is low immunity in Zamboanga City.

Barangay [smallest administrative division in the Philippines] Sangali recorded the most number of measles cases at 16, followed by Calarian with 10 cases; Arena Blanco with 6 cases; Busay (Sacol Island), San Jose Cawa-cawa, Sta Catalina, and Sta Maria with 4 cases each; Camino Nuevo, San Roque, Sinunuc, and Tumaga Tumaga with 3 cases each; Canelar, Cawit, Guiwan, Lumbangan, Lunzuran, Mercedes, Putik, and Tugbungan with 2 cases each. Another 24 other barangays listed with 1 case each, according to the CHO.

[Byline: Sheila Covarrubias]

