[6] Oklahoma (Norman, Cleveland county)
Date: Mon 12 Feb 2018
Source: Tahlequah Daily Press [edited]
http://www.tahlequahdailypress.com/news/oklahoma-state-department-of-health-confirms-measles-case/article_ceb5239e-1038-11e8-9f75-f31abb45fa71.html


The Oklahoma State Department of Health [OSDH] and the Cleveland County Health Department are investigating a confirmed case of measles in Norman located in Cleveland county. This is the 1st confirmed case in Oklahoma since 2015.

Measles was identified in a person who had returned to Oklahoma after international travel. Measles is a highly contagious respiratory disease and spreads through the air when an infected person coughs or sneezes. The virus may remain airborne up to 2 hours in a room after the person with measles has left an indoor area.

Based on collected information about the measles case during the time they were contagious, public health officials want to alert anyone who visited the locations in Norman [listed at the source URL above] about potential exposure to the measles virus:

The OSDH is collaborating with officials of these organizations to identify persons that may have visited the mentioned locations to inform them of their exposure and provide recommendations.

Persons are protected if they are immunized with 2 doses of a measles-containing vaccine after the 1st birthday, or if they were born during or before 1957.

Those who think they may have been at risk of exposure should review their immunization records and contact the Cleveland County Health Department; their local county health department; or the OSDH epidemiologist-on-call, 24/7/365 availability.

Persons who are susceptible to measles usually develop symptoms about 10 days after exposure with a range of 7-21 days. Symptoms of measles begin with a mild to moderate fever, runny nose, red eyes, and cough. A few days later, a rash appears starting on the face spreading to the rest of the body accompanied by a fever that can reach up to 105 deg F [40.6 deg C]. Measles can lead to pneumonia and other complications, especially in young children and adults over 20. The disease can also cause serious problems in pregnant women and those with weakened immune systems.

Individuals that were exposed and are not experiencing symptoms of illness do not need to be evaluated by a healthcare provider. Those who experience symptoms of illness suggestive of measles should contact their health care provider before presenting for care to discuss instructions for check-in and registration.

People with measles can spread the virus up to 4 days before the onset of the rash and until 4 days after the rash starts. Measles can be prevented with the measles vaccine (usually given in combination with rubella and mumps, called MMR vaccine), and is recommended for all children at 12-15 months of age and again at 4-6 years of age. If a person has not received a 2nd dose of the vaccine between 4-6 years of age, the booster dose may be given at any age thereafter. 2 doses of vaccine normally provide lifelong immunity.

